BACE legacy effects analysis

Eric R. Scott

28 July, 2021

1 Longitudinal Growth

1.1 Methods

To determine the effects of the historical and current precipitation treatments on crop growth, we analyzed the effects of the treatments on change in height over time. Because kale grows indeterminately , we used height data from the entire experiment from Jul 2 to Oct 9 (Figure 1.1a). Oats and beans, on the other hand, switched from growth to reproduction and we only used data from the growing phase to analyze effects on height (Figure 1.1b,c). This was Jul 2 to Aug 7 for oats and Jul 2 to Jul 31 for beans. We used linear mixed effects models to model height as a function of date, historical treatment, current treatment, their three-way interaction, and all two-way interactions among them. Additionally, early herbivory incidence (mainly small mammal herbivory) and house ID were included as fixed effects. Pot ID and plant ID were included as random effects. For kale and beans, height was log transformed to meet model assumptions. Height data for oats was left untransformed as the untransformed data better fit model assumptions of linearity and homogeneity of variances. Models were fit using the lme4 package (Bates et al., 2015). Because we were primarily interested in the fitted slope of height as a function of date, we focused our interpretation on two- and three-way interactions with date using the emtrends() function from the emmeans package (Lenth, 2021).

Figure 1.1: Weekly change in height of kale (a), beans (b), and oats (c).

The change in height over time is statistically significant (p < 0.001). There is a significant three-way interaction between day, historical treatment, and current treatment. This means that the slope of height over days depends on the interaction between historical and current treatment (I think; 3-way interactions are difficult to interpret) (Figure 1.2a).

Figure 1.2: Fitted growth rates from (generalized) linear mixed effects models of crop height as a function of day, herbivory, historical and current treatments, their interaction, and the three-way interaction between day, historical, and current treatments. For kale (a) and beans (b), the y-axis is fitted values from a log-link gaussian GLMM modeling exponential growth. For oats (c), the y-axis is fitted values from an identity-link model and represent linear growth rates.

2 Nutrient Analysis

2.1 Methods

To understand how current and historical precipitation treatments affected crop nutrients we used partial redundancy analysis (partial RDA), a supervised multivariate technique (Brocard, 2006). We modeled the effects of historical treatment, current treatment, their interaction, early herbivory (small mammal), and late herbivory (arthropods) on crop nutrients while controlling for the effect of house (i.e. house was used as a conditional variable and “partialed out”). Partial RDA was performed on centered and scaled nutrient data using the rda function from the vegan package (Oksanen et al., 2020). RDA significance was determined with permutation tests performed using the RVAideMemoire package (Hervé, 2021). Score plots and correlation plots were produced using packages ggplot2 (Wickham, 2016), ggrepel (Slowikowski, 2021), and ggpubr (Kassambara, 2020). When the RDA was significant, we followed up with univariate ANOVAs for log-transformed concentrations of Fe, Zn, and N.

NOTE: From the help file for rda() in case it is helpful for revising the methods:

Partial CCA (pCCA; or alternatively partial RDA) can be used to remove the effect of some conditioning or background or random variables or covariables before CCA proper. In fact, pCCA compares models cca(X ~ Z) and cca(X ~ Y + Z) and attributes their difference to the effect of Y cleansed of the effect of Z.

[in this case X is nutrients, Y is our predictors (current treatment, historical treatment, etc.) and Z is “house”]

NOTE jul_herbivory is cumulative herbivory in July, which was small-mammal herbivory. late_herbivory is the cumulative herbivory in August minus cumulative herbivory in July. Late herbivory was insect herbivory. So jul_herbivory is small mammal herbivory and late_herbivory is just the insect herbivory.

The first constrained component (the one that explains most of the variation due to predictors) explains about 54% of the variation explained by the predictors (less if you’d rather report the total variation in nutrients explained) (Figure 2.1a,b). This axis is negatively correlated with Fe, Cu, K, Al, etc (Figure 2.1a). Separation by historical and current treatment is minimal in the score plot (Figure 2.1b). Might be separation due to herbivory (not plotted)?

3 Biomass Analysis

3.1 Methods

To evaluate the effects of current and historical treatment on final biomass and root:shoot ratio, we used linear models (AKA ANOVAs) including historical treatment, current treatment, their interaction, early herbivory, late herbivory, and house as predictors.

If I remember correctly, this analysis only makes sense for kale.
